  <exercise label="variables-operators_exercises-ex-4">
    <statement>
      <p>The code below reads in a number of cents. Print out the number of quarters, dimes, nickles, and pennies required to make that amount. Separate each coin value by a space and do not print any other characters. For example, given 7 you should print <pf>0 0 1 2</pf> indicating 0 quarters, 0 dimes, 1 nickel, and 2 pennies. Given 143, you should print <pf>5 1 1 3</pf> indicating 5 quarters, 1 dime, 1 nickel, and 3 pennies.</p>
    </statement>
      <program
              interactive="activecode">
        <preamble>
<xi:include href="../../programs/variables-operators/exercises-2.cpp" parse="text"/>
        </preamble>
        <code>
    //Your code here
        </code>
        <postamble>
}
        </postamble>
        <tests>
        <iotest>
          <input>7</input>
          <output>0 0 1 2</output>
        </iotest>
        <iotest>
          <input>143</input>
          <output>5 1 1 3</output>
        </iotest>
        <iotest>
          <input>71</input>
          <output>2 2 0 1</output>
        </iotest>
        <iotest>
          <input>199</input>
          <output>7 2 0 4</output>
        </iotest>
        </tests>
      </program>
    <hint><p>This is like the Time Case Study. Use a combination of division and remainder. Work on one coin type at a time and make sure to progress in a consistent direction (either increasing or decreasing value).</p></hint>
  </exercise>

